<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2005-03-18T20:42:28-07:00</updated>
<published>2005-03-18T20:42:28-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=239&amp;p=1594#p1594</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=239&amp;p=1594#p1594"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Sleep Mode /Power Saving Mode for NES]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=239&amp;p=1594#p1594"><![CDATA[
GBA has two sleep modes: <ul><li>"Halt" stops clocking the CPU core until an interrupt is triggered but leaves the audio, the PPU, and background DMAs running. It's commonly used to wait for the vblank. </li><li>"Stop" stops clocking CPU, PPU, and audio until an interrupt is triggered. </li></ul> The Super NES has Halt as well by executing the 'wai' instruction.<br /><br />But because of how NES sound works, where one clock runs both the CPU and the audio but there is no 'wai' instruction like on 65c816, I don't think it'd be possible to make Halt. Stop, on the other hand, would involve intercepting the master clock signal on the NES mainboard.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Fri Mar 18, 2005 8:42 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
